Post_ID: 2761202702763851797 | Post_Code: CZRwzqLFoAV | Likes: 121 | Caption: Leave No Trace Principle 2: Travel and Camp on Durable Surfaces â¬‡ï¸<\br><\br>Continuing with our LNT series, letâ€™s talk about principle 2!<\br><\br>Choosing durable surfaces to travel and camp on greatly impacts the degradation of the environment. <\br><\br>ğŸ¥¾RULE OF THUMB: stay on the provided trails. Trails are built to be able to limit the destruction of the nearby areas, to keep the traffic in a designated area. So, whenever possible, stay on the trail.<\br><\br>ğŸ¥¾BUT, LETâ€™S BE REAL, there are times we have all gone off the trail! Whether youâ€™re searching for a private â€œbathroomâ€ area, taking a lunch break,  finding a campsite, or scrambling up some rock to get to a vista, itâ€™s just part of hiking! <\br><\br>ğŸª¨ Because of this, itâ€™s important to BE CONSCIOUS of where you travel off trail. Rocky areas are often able to withstand a lot more travel than vegetation and living soil. <\br><\br>ğŸ‘£ If you must travel through these areas, be conscious of your impact. (Sometimes this means spreading out from your group (vegetation), sometimes it means following exact footprints (soil))<\br><\br>ğŸ•CAMPING on durable surfaces:<\br>Choose a campsite that either already has very high traffic (no vegetation left) or, in less trafficked areas, find locations you can have the least impact on. Generally, rock and sand are great areas to set up camp, as they will be able to withstand campers. <\br><\br>â›ºï¸ğŸ¥˜CAMP COOKING: Set up camp kitchens on Rocky areas to avoid constant trampling on vegetation and soil. <\br><\br>This principle is EXTENSIVE and every situation differs. Your situation changes in different locations, the type of trip, and the local environment. We highly recommend you go check out lnt.org for more information on how to implement this principle, but we hope this gave you a good idea of the general guidelines!<\br><\br>Overall, it is our jobs to take into consideration the environment around us to decide how we can best limit our impact on each trip.<\br><\br>We also feel itâ€™s important to recognize that while â€œstay on the trailâ€ is a good rule of thumb, there are circumstances when you just CANâ€™T. Being able to know how to handle those moments and travel off trail responsibly is super important and can help us all to take better care of these lands! | Tags: [] | Time Stamp: 1643381034

Post_ID: 2760401047665658984 | Post_Code: CZO6iCrukxo | Likes: 158 | Caption: Want a simple way to help conserve the outdoors and pay it forward? Be Prepared for your outdoor experience. Being prepared lessens the strain on resources, especially in rural areas without a lot of resources. Knowing your experience level and planning for difficulties puts you in a better position to have a positive experience. Being prepared helps minimize the impacts to others. Or course, things can always go wrong, that's the nature of things (pun intended), but being properly prepared is a great way to minimize your personal impact.<\br><\br>Tips for better preparedness:<\br><\br>-Pack the 10 essentials<\br><\br>-know your limits<\br><\br>-Research your adventure beforehand<\br><\br>-Tell people of your plans before you go<\br><\br>as always, Adventure responsibly!<\br><\br>#adventureresponsibly #naturefirst  #wildernessculture #adventure #lnt #leaveitbetter #publiclands #nationalparks #hiking #camping #greatoutdoors #optoutside #protectthewild #cleanupyourshit #tagresponsibly #sidewiththeoutside #yourpubliclands #outdoorawareness | Tags: ['#adventureresponsibly', '#naturefirst', '#wildernessculture', '#adventure', '#lnt', '#leaveitbetter', '#publiclands', '#nationalparks', '#hiking', '#camping', '#greatoutdoors', '#optoutside', '#protectthewild', '#cleanupyourshit', '#tagresponsibly', '#sidewiththeoutside', '#yourpubliclands', '#outdoorawareness'] | Time Stamp: 1643285469

Post_ID: 2760078930242506807 | Post_Code: CZNxSndJRA3 | Likes: 106 | Caption: Before and after - this is what campsite restoration looks like! <\br><\br>Picture 1 shows an illegal campsite that had been heavily used, leaving the area without vegetation or healthy soil. Picture 2 shows the area after the soil has been decompacted to allow for aeration, moisture retention, and root growth. It was then covered in a layer of topsoil and dead vegetation. If left alone, this vegetation will start to decompose, adding necessary nutrients back into the soil and returning this patch to a healthy state. <\br><\br>Rangers and restoration crews work hard to return these areas to their natural state. If you see something that looks like picture 2, please leave it as is and find a more sustainable spot to stop!<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>#restoration #rangers #jmt #johnmuirtrail #wildernessrestoration #sustainable #camping #natural #naturalization #leavenotrace #lnt | Tags: ['#restoration', '#rangers', '#jmt', '#johnmuirtrail', '#wildernessrestoration', '#sustainable', '#camping', '#natural', '#naturalization', '#leavenotrace', '#lnt'] | Time Stamp: 1643247070

Post_ID: 2759941819536871849 | Post_Code: CZNSHZKPZGp | Likes: 24 | Caption: Happy #WildernessWednesday! Today we're taking in the beauty found in the San Gorgonio Wilderness in Southern California! Nestled in San Bernardino National Forest, this designated wilderness also resides within the Sand to Snow National Monument. <\br>.<\br>The San Gorgonio Wilderness consists of sub-alpine landscape surrounded by desert to the east, and covers 94,000+ acres. With elevations from 4,400'-11,500', you can experience soft rolling foothills, to canyons, to steep, impressive mountains. Due to the elevation gradient, this wilderness has a transition between desert, coastal and mountain environments, including the different types of vegetation representative of each elevation.<\br>.<\br>The U.S. Congress designated the San Gorgonio Wilderness in 1964, making it one of the first designated wilderness areas in the U.S. The wilderness is named after San Gorgonio Mountain, which at 11,499 ft. is the highest peak in California south of the Sierra Nevada. San Gorgonio Mountain, however, was originally known as "Old Grayback" by locals until officially designated by the US Geological Survey in 1899.<\br>.<\br>There are 81 miles of trails in the National Forest section of the Wilderness, and ~20 miles of the Pacific Crest National Scenic Trail in the Bureau of Land Management portion. <\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>#willdernessvolunteers #givingsomethingback #wildernesswednesdays  #sangoroniowilderness #sangorgonio #sangorgoniopeak #sangorgoniopass #usfs #sanbernardinonationalforest #itsallyours #usforestservice #designatedwilderness #pacificcresttrail #pct #bureauoflandmanagement #blm #california #oldgraybackmountain #oldgrayback #optoutside #leavenotrace #lnt #photography #wilderness #camping #backpacking #colorpalette #colors #colorwheel | Tags: ['#WildernessWednesday', '#willdernessvolunteers', '#givingsomethingback', '#wildernesswednesdays', '#sangoroniowilderness', '#sangorgonio', '#sangorgoniopeak', '#sangorgoniopass', '#usfs', '#sanbernardinonationalforest', '#itsallyours', '#usforestservice', '#designatedwilderness', '#pacificcresttrail', '#pct', '#bureauoflandmanagement', '#blm', '#california', '#oldgraybackmountain', '#oldgrayback', '#optoutside', '#leavenotrace', '#lnt', '#photography', '#wilderness', '#camping', '#backpacking', '#colorpalette', '#colors', '#colorwheel'] | Time Stamp: 1643230725
Post_ID: 2759927452602728610 | Post_Code: CZNO2U6PACi | Likes: 7 | Caption: YOU ARE WORTH IT<\br>Make investing in yourself your new habit. If you are not worth your own time and money, then what is? You wouldn't even be able to enjoy anything in life without being physically and mentally healthy in the first place. Then why not invest in the things that make you happy and healthy, every day? The same goes for relationships, we may put others' happiness and wellbeing before our own, but how can we help anyone if we are not feeling well? You can't save anybody from drowning if you are struggling yourself. In a plane accident, you gotta put on your own oxygen mask first. The thing is that investing in yourself IS scary, it takes courage to face the fear of failure in exploring your own darkness and pursuing your dreams. I know it well, I've been there, dazed and confused for a long time. Not that I got it all figured out nowadays, but after a lot of work on myself and years of study, I have the tools to navigate difficult situations (like moving overseas on my own while starting an online business after a burnout and a breakup ğŸ˜‚). Most importantly, I keep investing in myself EVERY SINGLE DAY. Through healthy habits, moving my body, fueling it with clean nutritious food, cultivating gratitude and positive thoughts, journalling, coaching, study, yoga and self-inquiry. I have spent thousands in this and dedicate many hours to it every day, because I love it so much that I have made it my job, but you don't have to take that long or spend that much. As little as 5 or 15 minutes, however much time you can find in your day, will have a ripple effect if you make it a habit. Your investment in yourself may be some daily stretching or workout, a walk outdoors or a dance in your kitchen, a morning gratitude list or an evening meditation. It may be quitting the job that you don't like, or asking for a promotion. It may be breaking the relationship where you are no longer happy, or going all in and commiting fully. Post_ID: 2759266281629246075 | Post_Code: CZK4hBdOWJ7 | Likes: 48 | Caption: This is the sorghum mill at the Lyon Farm, one of the many agricultural outbuildings that dots the historic site (here, @flatrockarchives Co-Founder Johnny Waits leads a tour of the site to discuss its connection to the historic Flat Rock community). Sorghum syrup is similar to maple syrup or molasses, a sweet, sticky concoction derived form the sorghum plant. To make sorghum syrup, you crush the stalks of the sorghum plant, which produces a juice. The juice is then boiled, so that excess water evaporates as steam and only the sweet syrup remains.<\br>The Lyon family enslaved people prior to the Civil War, and continued to live on and farm the Lyon property until the early 2000's. This mill was used by later generations of the Lyon family as they worked on the farm. You can experience the full tour of the Flat Rock Archives by signing up for an @airbnb experience, where Johnny Waits leads you on a tour through Flat Rock's history, from enslavement to the present day.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>#ArabiaMountainNationalHeritageArea #ArabiaMountain #PanolaMountain #NationalHeritageArea#NationalPark #NationalHistoricSite #StatePark #GAStateParks #GeorgiaStatePark #Parks #Hiking #HikeLife #WanderNorthGA #AtlantaTrails #RespectThePark #LeaveNoTrace #OptOutside #RecreateResponsibly #LNT #history #blackhistory #sorghum | Tags: ['#ArabiaMountainNationalHeritageArea', '#ArabiaMountain', '#PanolaMountain', '#NationalHeritageArea', '#NationalPark', '#NationalHistoricSite', '#StatePark', '#GAStateParks', '#GeorgiaStatePark', '#Parks', '#Hiking', '#HikeLife', '#WanderNorthGA', '#AtlantaTrails', '#RespectThePark', '#LeaveNoTrace', '#OptOutside', '#RecreateResponsibly', '#LNT', '#history', '#blackhistory', '#sorghum'] | Time Stamp: 1643150194

Nude Beach and Caveman show up and we start hiking again. We enter a massive section of blowdowns and our pace slows way down. By noon we've only done about five miles. Post_ID: 2758599709314381047 | Post_Code: CZIg9HnLfT3 | Likes: 33 | Caption: I spent the weekend renewing my Wilderness First Responder certification with @nolsedu ğŸ’‰ğŸ©¸<\br><\br>And it reminded me how much can go WRONG, especially in remote environments ğŸ¤• <\br><\br>What gives me confidence, though, is the fact that planning ahead and preparing really DOES help prevent accidents. <\br><\br>And an ounce of prevention IS worth a pound of cureâ€¦ <\br><\br>Here are some ways you can avoid catastrophe on your next trip into the backcountry: <\br><\br>ğŸ‘‰ bring a first aid kit! The size/contents of your kit can fluctuate based on how many people are in your group, where you are traveling (remoteness) and for how long, and the activities youâ€™ll be doing<\br><\br>ğŸ‘‰ have a plan incase of emergency; who will you contact for help? Know how to deliver a detailed patient report to EMS/SAR in the event you need an evacuation, and make sure you have an exit strategy, even if it is just marching back out the way you came <\br><\br>ğŸ‘‰ seek out first aid training! A WFA is more affordable but less comprehensive than a WFR, and a WEMT is the most comprehensive wilderness medicine cert you can obtain (check out @nolsedu for more course info)<\br><\br>ğŸ‘‰ lastly, know your limits. If you plan to go BIG, do so with the understanding that you might have to bail, and make sure you CAN bail, some routes are more committing than others. <\br><\br>Anytime we go out into the backcountry, we do so knowing that there is some risk involved. And when (if) we call for help, we are asking others to put their lives on the line for us. <\br><\br>Traveling safely and sustainably in the backcountry is an intentional practice ğŸŒ±<\br><\br>Photo of Jai carrying the @gossamergear Mariposa, ğŸ“¸ taken by @mountainmagicmedia <\br><\br>#shetreks #wildernessmedicine #emergencypreparedness #backpacking #adventurecompany #womenwhobackpack #firstaid #planaheadandprepare #lnt #safetravels #nolswildernessmedicine #gossamergear | Tags: ['#shetreks', '#wildernessmedicine', '#emergencypreparedness', '#backpacking', '#adventurecompany', '#womenwhobackpack', '#firstaid', '#planaheadandprepare', '#lnt', '#safetravels', '#nolswildernessmedicine', '#gossamergear'] | Time Stamp: 1643070733

Post_ID: 2756446639363583806 | Post_Code: CZA3Z09le8- | Likes: 9 | Caption: Day 100 (Sat 7/24); Lander, Wyoming<\br><\br>This morning after we packed up and were in the process of heading to breakfast, we learned from someone we were passing that there was a farmers market in the park. So we decided to stay there and get breakfast from the local vendors, and we also learned that an art festival was happening concurrently in the park. We hung out for the beginning of the art fair and watched the local fire department child drum and bagpipe corp perform. We then left to get more caffeine, meet up with Nude Beach who stayed in a hotel, check out the gear store, and hangout out the library to charge up our batteries. The librarians remembered us from yesterday and our glowing review of the library. They took our pictures and asked us to write something because apparently the library is regularly on the chopping block when it comes to city budget. Bison asks to play the piano in the little theatre room we saw, and they ended up taking us to the original library building, which was a Carnegie Library (look it up) that has a baby grand piano. We play piano, sing, charge, and download for a few hours before we head out for a late lunch. We then went back to the pool for another soak before resupplying, where we run into Nibbles and Threshold! We pick up Dominos pizza, head back to the park to celebrate Christmas in July by watching Christmas television episodes, then sleep in the dugout again. Post_ID: 2755515710706169847 | Post_Code: CY9jvCFpjf3 | Likes: 22 | Caption: Day 99 (Fri 7/23) 3 Trail Miles & A Hitch into Lander<\br><\br>We woke up this morning and packed up immediately without breakfast because we only had about an hour of hiking before we'd get to the road. I'm in a much better mood knowing that we're out of the Basin and about to relax in town with some hikers who are ahead of us. We throw out the thumb and get picked up by an RV covered in cartoon characters and with three cats inside. It's piloted by a nice retired couple who let their grandchildren paint the outside. They drop us off at the post office, we grab our packages with our bear gear (we're heading into grizzly territory!), and then get McDonald's. We then go into tow and, hit up the library to upload podcast recordings. We check out the church where there is supposedly going to be a community potluck later, go eat some very tasty ice cream, and then head to the local high school where the pool is open for public use. We make use of the showers, and it turns out there's a hot tub at this high school??? We soak in it for a while and make conversation with Jenn, who's there with her kids. Jenn gives us a lift to the laundromat, pays for our laundry, and even offers us dinner and her trampoline to sleep on! Jenn's the best! Nude Beach shows up while we're doing laundry, and afterwards we hangout at Gannet Grill & Bar with other hikers in town. We make a (slightly buzzed) walk to the park where they let people camp. It's dark and we're not quite sure where the camping is, so we end up sleeping in the dugout of the baseball fields (we learned our lesson from the sprinklers in Creede).<\br><\br>#newmexico #colorado #wyoming #idaho #montana #embracethebrutality #thetrek #hikingaddict #gooutside #staywild #hikertrash #continentaldividetrail #cdt2021 #mexicotocanada #backpacking #thruhike  #optoutside #camping #longdistancehiking #outdoors #choosemountains #LNT #leavenotrace #camp #summercamp #funnestknowntime | Tags: ['#newmexico', '#colorado', '#wyoming', '#idaho', '#montana', '#embracethebrutality', '#thetrek', '#hikingaddict', '#gooutside', '#staywild', '#hikertrash', '#continentaldividetrail', '#cdt2021', '#mexicotocanada', '#backpacking', '#thruhike', '#optoutside', '#camping', '#longdistancehiking', '#outdoors', '#choosemountains', '#LNT', '#leavenotrace', '#camp', '#summercamp', '#funnestknowntime'] | Time Stamp: 1642703091
Post_ID: 2755512673486295373 | Post_Code: CY9jC1dPNFN | Likes: 47 | Caption: Should you build a fire?<\br>The most important consideration to be made when deciding to use a fire is the potential damage to the backcountry.<\br>What is the fire danger for the time of year and the location you have selected? n Are there administrative restrictions from the agency that administers the area?<\br>Is there sufficient wood so its removal will not be noticeable?<\br>Does the harshness of alpine and desert growing conditions for trees and shrubs mean that the regeneration of wood sources cannot keep pace with the demand for firewood?<\br>Do group members possess the skill to build a campfire that will Leave No Trace?<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br> #leavenotrace #lnt #nature #naturephotography #getoutinthewoods #outdoorlifetgroughmylens #forest #forestview #mountainviewpnw #hike #hiking #hikingparadise #hikingbangers #bootsonthetrail #hikingadventures #hikingtheworld #coastalhikingtrail #trailview #britishcolumbianature #britishcolumbia #VancouverIsland #vancouverislandhiking #westcoastwonderland #explorevi #explorenanaimo #centralvancouverisland #VancouverIslandtrails #valhallakingdom #woodsexplorer<\br>#leavenotracethursday via @preview.app | Tags: ['#leavenotrace', '#lnt', '#nature', '#naturephotography', '#getoutinthewoods', '#outdoorlifetgroughmylens', '#forest', '#forestview', '#mountainviewpnw', '#hike', '#hiking', '#hikingparadise', '#hikingbangers', '#bootsonthetrail', '#hikingadventures', '#hikingtheworld', '#coastalhikingtrail', '#trailview', '#britishcolumbianature', '#britishcolumbia', '#VancouverIsland', '#vancouverislandhiking', '#westcoastwonderland', '#explorevi', '#explorenanaimo', '#centralvancouverisland', '#VancouverIslandtrails', '#valhallakingdom', '#woodsexplorer', '#leavenotracethursday'] | Time Stamp: 1642702729

Post_ID: 2754727615202270259 | Post_Code: CY6wiu9Fxwz | Likes: 20 | Caption: Day 98 (Thu 7/22): 30ish miles<\br><\br>We wake up in the morning to find Bison camped next to us. We eat breakfast and pack up while he tells us about how he accidentally went 8-10 miles off trail yesterday. We then hike out. It's another long day of desert hiking, but we are actually on roads for a decent amount of it. I'm very fed up with the Basin at this point and am wishing any car would stop for a little bit of trail magic. We also start passing a bunch of posts for the Oregon Trail? And the California Trail, whatever that is? Near the end of the day I get to the water source I was planning on stopping at, but unfortunately it's a terrible spot. The next one is only a mile, so I suck it up and hike for another 20ish minutes. I am so glad I decided to go an extra mile because I arrive in South Pass City, a historical mining town, that now operates as a sort of museum/recreation area (Conner Prairie on a way smaller scale, for those from Fishers). There's a bathroom, piped water, and a spot where they let backpackers set up. I roll in at dusk, set up to cowboy camp and hang out with a with a guy cycling the Divide. Bison shows up, and later Nude Beach does as well. Bison warns me that it's probably going to rain and offers to let me sleep under his tarp so I don't have to set up my tent. I agree and help him set it up, which was a good call because it definitely stormed. Post_ID: 2754126812384548008 | Post_Code: CY4n75uj1So | Likes: 914 | Caption: Planning winter action? Donâ€™t forget your traction! When it comes to trekking winter trails, traction devices are a must to help keep you on your feet:<\br>ğŸ‘ Snowshoes are large frames that attach to your boots and prevent you from sinking deep into snow by distributing your weight over a greater surface area. Snowshoes also prevent postholing (when bare boots make deep holes in the snow), which can be hazardous for you and other visitors. Snowshoes should be worn wherever there is significant snowpack, and they are required in the Adirondack High Peaks Wilderness once snow depths reach 8 or more inches.<\br>ğŸ‘ Hiking spikes pull on over your boots and are simple to put on/take off, making them easy to pack. Spike versions are best for flatter backwoods outings because they grip icy trails but can be worn down when used on hard surfaces like sidewalks or roads. Versions that use coils or studs arenâ€™t secure on ice but can help with traction in light snow or on maintained trails.<\br>ğŸ‘ Crampons are larger, sharper spikes on frames that attach to your boots. They penetrate ice, making them the best choice for thick ice and steep slopes.<\br><\br>No matter which is best for your adventure, remember to practice putting on and using your gear in a safe and familiar environment first. Picking the right footwear is just one part of planning ahead and preparing for a safe and enjoyable time outside. <\br><\br>(Pictured, in order: snowshoes, hiking spikes/microspikes, crampons) | Tags: [] | Time Stamp: 1642537522

Post_ID: 2732341312255098420 | Post_Code: CXrOfJqFv40 | Likes: 26 | Caption: Day 75 (Tue 6/29): ??? miles<\br><\br>So after a rough night (no water, mildly heavy winds) I wake up and find that Nude Beach arrived later, that we passed Bison in the dark, and that we weren't too far from each other. No PDF, though. So I pack up and we start a steep, dangerous descent. There's no visible trail and it's all scree (small rocks that basically act as marbles when hiking). I'm very happy I didn't try to do this at night. I fall on my butt a few times, and after finally reaching the bottom and getting to water I find that both my water bottles had fallen out. Bison gave me one of his to use until we get to town. After regrouping with Nude Beach we have a meal break before starting a wild climb up and through the Argentine Ridge. This is the knifiest ridge ever, and as we get close to Gray's Peak (the highest point on trail) we are enveloped by clouds again. We get a message from PDF, who took a low route last evening and stopped just short of where we had planned to stop (but didn't make it to). He then got up early thinking we were ahead and was up and over Gray's Peak already. So we're feeling better about that, and we're feeling worse as we ascend the mountain because we hear thunder near the top. The worst place you can be when there may be lightning. We lose each other because of the clouds, but I run up to the top, snap a selfie (which I don't show now because it looks the same as my photo from yesterday), and start descending immediately. Luckily the other side is a well maintained trail and is easy to move quickly on. Once I clear the weather and feel safer, I start to run because I'm hungry and know at the end of this long dirt road is Bison's mom and aunt who will take us for food. We get picked up and find that his family made t-shirts from us! We go for dinner, grab Epson salts and breakfast foods, then back to the hotel.<\br><\br>Albums: Bacchanal 'N' Philadelphia by Mischief Brew. Approaching Thunder by We The Heathens. Chad Hates George self titled album. | Tags: [] | Time Stamp: 1639940512

Post_ID: 2752627933955714395 | Post_Code: CYzTIWaP21b | Likes: 33 | Caption: Day 95 (Mon 7/19) 28ish miles<\br><\br>Bison and I woke up not quite so early as we had planned this morning due to the evening caffeine we consumed when we had planned to hike out the night before. We then pack up and leave to start our return to desert trail in The Great Basin. Whoof, it's not nearly as novel this time around. We get to the first water source, and some new friends show up. We also catch up with Nude Beach. We have high-noon style water duels with our sport capped and culo clean capped bottles. Then we have to get back to hiking, which includes road walking. A very kind man with water in his truck tops us off and we take a late afternoon break in the shade under some rocks. We hike into the night to get to the next water source, where we find friends new and old there. We cowboy camp, and also there's a lot of cows around because it's a water source in the desert. I keep one eye open throughout the night because one cow keeps coming into our area, and I don't trust cows.<\br><\br>Albums: Good of That by Lucy Michelle and The Velvet Lapelles. Although Leave No Trace has its roots in backcountry settings, the actions can be applied anywhere â€” from remote wilderness areas, to local parks and even in your own backyard.<\br> <\br>Follow these seven points to minimize your impact on the outdoors: <\br>â€¢	Plan ahead and prepare <\br>â€¢	Travel and camp on durable surfaces <\br>â€¢	Dispose of waste properly <\br>â€¢	Leave what you find <\br>â€¢	Minimize campfire impacts <\br>â€¢	Respect wildlife <\br>â€¢	Be considerate of other visitors <\br><\br>Share your best Leave No Trace tips in the comments.<\br><\br>Happy adventuring! <\br><\br>Photo/Emily Isabelle <\br>Image: View of craggy cliffside shoreline on Anacapa Island<\br><\br>#LNT#KnowBeforeYouGo | Tags: ['#LNT', '#KnowBeforeYouGo'] | Time Stamp: 1642291234

Create a trail around the yard or neighborhood for others to track.<\br><\br>Remember to keep a safe distance and practice Leave No Trace Principles. <\br>- - -<\br>#gsmeFreshAirFridays #AnimalTracks #SnowTracks #CreateYourOwnTracks #Footprints #GetCrafty #CardboardCutout #SnowBoots #GetOutdoors #OutdoorFun #Winter #WinterFun #Snow #LeaveNoTrace #LeaveNoTracePrinciples #LNT #GirlScoutsOfMaine #GirlScouts | Tags: ['#gsmeFreshAirFridays', '#AnimalTracks', '#SnowTracks', '#CreateYourOwnTracks', '#Footprints', '#GetCrafty', '#CardboardCutout', '#SnowBoots', '#GetOutdoors', '#OutdoorFun', '#Winter', '#WinterFun', '#Snow', '#LeaveNoTrace', '#LeaveNoTracePrinciples', '#LNT', '#GirlScoutsOfMaine', '#GirlScouts'] | Time Stamp: 1642172730

Post_ID: 2750386598719689827 | Post_Code: CYrVgoTrpRj | Likes: 41 | Caption: ALIGNMENT<\br>In the dictionary, alignment has to do with arranging on a straight line or correct position, which may or not be synonymous (luckily, life's hardly ever about straight lines, as much as we would like it to be sometimes). In yoga, we care, and sometimes even obsess ğŸ˜‚ over alignment for our poses: take the one pictured here, pincha mayurasana. The first pic is from a few months ago in Italy. I was helped to get up there, but once I could stack my hips over my shoulders in a (more or less) straight line, the position would almost hold itself. So the picture gives the illusion of stability, but I needed help to align myself. Fast-forward to today in my Brazilian living room: I still struggle with this on my mat almost every day, so I use a 3-step progression with the help of a block to align the hips on top of the shoulders. Firstly I put my head on a block (wonderful @mfmarquezd trick ğŸ˜), then I let the block sit between my hands with free head, finally I do without block. It's harder without because my hips are not as aligned on top of my shoulders when I kick up, mainly due to me being afraid of being upside down without any support. The lesson here is: IT'S THE SAME WITH LIFE. Once you are aligned, with your purpose, your routines, your surroundings, everything flows easily. But when you are not, Oh my is it a struggle. I have discovered that a little help from a pair of eyes outside the situation goes a long way to bring us into alignment and get over the fear. A little support, a little push even. I used to try to power through life's struggles (with so much unnecessary drama), but yoga has taught me the importance of alignment, to give up the drama and go with the flow. I have learnt to use the flow to carry me where I wanna go, with fiery determination but also compassionate patience. I have also learnt the importance of letting myself be helped: by my yoga teachers, by other healers and experts, by my own coach. With these posts, I hope to inspire you, like I was by many social media accounts during the pandemic. And maybe I can help you with alignment in yoga or in life, too. Post_ID: 2749875018094563670 | Post_Code: CYphMJuP1FW | Likes: 45 | Caption: It's #WildernessWednesday and today we're sharing photos from the Ansel Adams Wilderness areas in the Sierra National Forest. Tucked in the dramatic granite landscape of the Sierra Nevada mountain range, the Ansel Adams Wilderness encompasses 232,000 spectacular acres of granite peaks, steep-walled gorges, and rock outcroppings. <\br>.<\br>Several small glaciers cling to north and northeast facing slopes of the highest peaks. There are also a number of fairly large lakes on the eastern slope of the precipitous Ritter Range. Elevations range from 3,500 feet to 13,157 feet. The area includes approximately 350 miles of trails, including portions of the John Muir and Pacific Crest Trails. <\br>.<\br>79,000 acres of the Ansel Adams Wilderness are managed by the Inyo National Forest, while the remainder is managed by the Sierra National Forest and Devilâ€™s Postpile National Monument. Ansel Adams Wilderness offers some beautiful views, outdoor enrichment, and some opportunities for solitude. Post_ID: 2749802954775836397 | Post_Code: CYpQzfhu7bt | Likes: 70 | Caption: This is a solution pit, a depression in the surface of the rock outcrops. Youâ€™ll find them anywhere there are rock outcrops in the National Heritage Area, especially in Davidson-Arabia Mountain Nature Preserve (@arabiaranger) and Panola Mountain State Park (@panolamountainstatepark). Solution pits take thousands of years to form in the rock face, a process that begins with two things: lichen and water. Water, as it falls on the outcrops, slowly erodes the granite. Meanwhile, lichen grows on the bare rock surface and releases a weak acid that reacts with the stone to, over time, further erode and indent the rock. These processes take place in geologic time, meaning that everything is very slow: thousands of years pass before a solution put looks like the ones you see today.<\br>As you hike, take care of the solution pits and stick to the bare granite. Remember, water on the outcrops is ephemeral, and solution pits sometimes are just filled with dry, sandy soil. By sticking to bare stone, we can leave solution pits in place to continue their slow geologic growth.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>#ArabiaMountainNationalHeritageArea #ArabiaMountain #PanolaMountain #NationalHeritageArea#NationalPark #NationalHistoricSite #StatePark #GAStateParks #GeorgiaStatePark #Parks #Hiking #HikeLife #WanderNorthGA #AtlantaTrails #RespectThePark #LeaveNoTrace #OptOutside #RecreateResponsibly #LNT | Tags: ['#ArabiaMountainNationalHeritageArea', '#ArabiaMountain', '#PanolaMountain', '#NationalHeritageArea', '#NationalPark', '#NationalHistoricSite', '#StatePark', '#GAStateParks', '#GeorgiaStatePark', '#Parks', '#Hiking', '#HikeLife', '#WanderNorthGA', '#AtlantaTrails', '#RespectThePark', '#LeaveNoTrace', '#OptOutside', '#RecreateResponsibly', '#LNT'] | Time Stamp: 1642022078

Post_ID: 2749091059255795551 | Post_Code: CYmu8DKJN9f | Likes: 30 | Caption: My thoughts on access<\br><\br>My buddy @aidan.pinsk recently posted on his account with some thoughts about access, and it got me inspired to make a post that I think is a bit overdue for me.<\br><\br>Access is a huge part in the developing world of Outdoor Rec. The OR world is predominantly white, strong men. Women have not been shown in the OAE world, but many organizations like NOLS and Outward Bound are trying to improve on that. <\br><\br>I think we need to be more inclusive with other minority groups like BIPOC, AAPI, and LGBTQ. Adding them into sports that they may not be able to afford or make them feel comfortable in a climbing gym where they're the minority. I have personally experienced this while working at my local climbing gym. I've seen men really enjoy the sport and ask questions on how they can get stronger but I have also seen women who are new to the sport not really enjoy it because they feel weak or not invited. Some have approached me after they try it out, some have dropped little hints while I am walking around checking in on guests, some even feel uncertainty or uncomfortable while i'm just doing a basic orientation on the facility. When people ask about getting their own gear, I always tell them that it's going to cost you $250+ for a full set of gear, and that tends to draw people away, especially those of lower income. But I have to be honest as a salesperson and staff member. <\br><\br>Also commenting on what Aidan spoke about, do research on the lands you live on, the lands you recreate on, look at the historical impact they may have and protect those lands. There's so many access battles that are going on that are unheard of. We just recently got back Bears Ears, but are now in a battle for The Grand Tetons. Even just tiny things like using boars hair brushes to brush off rock holds or like Aidan mentioned, using rosin-less chalk. LNT (Leave No Trace) is a principle that needs to be publicized and standardized across the world. Pack it in, pack it out. Leave the area you were recreating at cleaner than it was when you got there. If you see trash that isn't yours, take it with you and throw it away. <\br><\br>Continued in comments â¬‡ï¸<\br><\br>#lnt #leavenotrace #access | Tags: ['#lnt', '#leavenotrace', '#access'] | Time Stamp: 1641937213

Post_ID: 2746877500487806990 | Post_Code: CYe3oh6FrAO | Likes: 19 | Caption: Day 92 (Fri 7/16): Impromptu 24 Hour Challenge<\br><\br>Nude Beach and and woke up and started hiking this morning hoping to run into Bison. We don't see him but do run into Sugar Mama, and at some point we accidentally take a wrong turn on a backcountry road and get off trail. When we get to the paved road that takes us into the next town, we still haven't seen Bison. I try and figure out what he may have done while we eat lunch. We had talked about doing an overnight hike into town, but hadn't agreed necessarily. After some road walk I assume that he had decided to do that, so I stop and set up my tent to take a nap and prepare for a night hike. I then hear Bison and Sugar Mama roll up, and I start hiking again. Bison suggests we do the night hike, starting an impromptu 24 Hour Challenge into Rawlins for breakfast. We all slowly drifted apart in the evening. Nude Beach was out around 1am. I went to about 2:30am when I sat down for a quick break and could barely walk when I got back up. So I cowboy camp in the ditch of this deserted highway for about three hours until the sun comes up. These principles are a set of guidelines that are meant to minimize human impact for anyone visiting the outdoors: <\br><\br>1. Plan ahead and prepare<\br>2. Travel and camp on durable surfaces<\br>3. Dispose of waste properly<\br>4. Leave what you find<\br>5. Minimize campfire impacts<\br>6. Respect wildlife<\br>7. Be considerate of other visitors <\br><\br>While these were originally developed for exploration of the backcountry, they are equally applicable in frontcountry locations or anywhere outside! South Rockdale Community Park (3909 East Fairview Road SW)&nbsp;Another connection point to the paved Arabia Mountain PATH trail, the South Rockdale Community Park includes trails that run through forest and along the South River.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>#ArabiaMountainNationalHeritageArea #ArabiaMountain #PanolaMountain #NationalHeritageArea#NationalPark #NationalHistoricSite #StatePark #GAStateParks #GeorgiaStatePark #Parks #Hiking #HikeLife #WanderNorthGA #AtlantaTrails #RespectThePark #LeaveNoTrace #OptOutside #RecreateResponsibly #LNT | Tags: ['#ArabiaMountainNationalHeritageArea', '#ArabiaMountain', '#PanolaMountain', '#NationalHeritageArea', '#NationalPark', '#NationalHistoricSite', '#StatePark', '#GAStateParks', '#GeorgiaStatePark', '#Parks', '#Hiking', '#HikeLife', '#WanderNorthGA', '#AtlantaTrails', '#RespectThePark', '#LeaveNoTrace', '#OptOutside', '#RecreateResponsibly', '#LNT'] | Time Stamp: 1641591532

Post_ID: 2746137580335471893 | Post_Code: CYcPZRkPx0V | Likes: 31 | Caption: RADICAL RESPONSIBILITY FOR RADICAL FREEDOM<\br>Do you want to be free? Freedom has been one of my main goals, if not the main one, for my whole life. Since I was a child, I've never liked to be told what to do. As a teenager, I thought that freedom entailed to rebel against authority, to party and get wasted. This went on into adulthood, when travelling was added to partying in an attempt to break free from a routine that felt boring and unmotivating. And I was lucky enough to be economically supported by my family while I studied in university for many years, in different countries. All my material needs were covered, I could organize my days as I pleased (other than studying), but was I free? I would regularly feel trapped in a life that felt wrong, but I didn't know what to do, so I just distracted and numbed myself and kept going to the next degree, the next job, the next relationship, the next trip, the next party. All this has only changed THANKS TO MY MENTAL HEALTH PROBLEMS. Yes, I say THANKS because any health issues, especially mental ones, are just a message, an indicator that something is wrong with us and we need to change our approach to life. Only when shit got real for me, when I started having daily anxiety, crying fits and suicidal thoughts I had the motivation to REALLY search for answers, to really look into the bottom of my heart and soul, to really take my health into my own hands. How? By OWNING MY PROBLEMS. Every single one. By taking radical responsibility for everything that was not working in my life, and committing to doing something about each single thing I didn't like. By stopping looking for someone to blame, and start finding something to do to fix the problem. Because it doesn't matter whose fault your issues are (disclaimer: our problems are most often of our own creation), what matters is that the only person that can do something to solve them and transform your life is ultimately YOU. And if you don't do anything and just keep going on auto-pilot, know that your subconscious (often limiting) beliefs acquired from your family, school and society since childhood are the ones running your life. So what are you gonna do about that? | Tags: [] | Time Stamp: 1641585131

Post_ID: 2745426405479481969 | Post_Code: CYZtsUXlQJx | Likes: 18 | Caption: Day 90 (Wed 7/14): Into Encampment, Wyoming<\br><\br>Last out of camp this morning as everyone else we were with is an early riser and also I wanted to rest more after exhausting myself yesterday getting lost and running out of water. I managed to get to the road just after @graceluscher and @heyspamcake though. They had been waiting for at least half an hour by then. A number of hikers arrive, so to improve our chances of getting a ride all of the men move to a ditch out of site (women tend to have a better chance of someone stopping, so the trick is to wait until someone stops, then ask if they have room for more). Even with four women throwing their thumbs out we didn't have any luck. So I decided that a hitch will come if I'm doing something that would be inconvenient for me if a car were to stop. So I start making a sandwich. Sure enough a pickup truck stopped as I took a bite. I pick up my new shoes at the post office, then take a quick dip on the hot springs the next town over. We resupply at the grocery store, then hip back over to Encampment to celebrate Two Taps birthday again at a bar. Post_ID: 2743319382263311804 | Post_Code: CYSOnGFP628 | Likes: 32 | Caption: Happy Monday! We're kicking off 2022 by sharing some of the kinds of work Wilderness Volunteers does on our stewardship projects.<\br>.<\br>This November, our 2021 Leader Trainees spent the week in the San Rafael Swell in east-central Utah. Their challenge: removing the invasive tamarisk from the wash, to reinforce annual removal efforts. <\br>.<\br>What is tamarisk you ask? Tamarisk is an invasive shrub or small tree that is found across the American West. Also known as salt cedar, Tamarisk is a thirsty plant with a high evapotranspiration rate, taking lots of water and releasing it into the air. It competes with native plants and can displace riparian habitats. This invasive species can and does alter habitat quality for some wildlife, water use by floodplain vegetation, and the frequency and intensity of wildfires.<\br>.<\br>Our crew of leader trainees diligently worked in the North Fork Coal Wash with a thoughtful strategy to attack sections of the wash, coordinating the cutting, flagging, and moving on so a finishing spray could be applied no later than 10 minutes after the cut. Our agency partners assisted in big tamarisk cutting jobs with chainsaw support and managed all aspects of spraying.<\br>.<\br>This project was an excellent practice in communication, coordination, patience, and we are very thankful and proud of our leader trainee crew! Y'all rose to the challenge, worked cohesively with each other, and removed a lot of cumbersome, intertwined tamarisk. We thank you for your hard work, we thank the BLM folks at the Price Field Office, and we look forward to heading back in 2023 to see how our efforts held up. <\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>#wildernessvolunteers #givingsomethingback #wv2021SanRafaelSwell #stewardship #conservation #SanRafaelSwell #SanRafaelSwellRecreationArea #theswell #northforkcoalwash #bureauoflandmanagement #blm #tamariskremoval #tamarisk #saltcedar #invasive #utah #leavenotrace #lnt #clipping #cutting #slipperarch #thedrips #swaseysarch #volunteer #hiking  #SidsMountainWildernessStudyArea #sidsmountain #swamping #sandstonecanyon #naturalarches | Tags: ['#wildernessvolunteers', '#givingsomethingback', '#wv2021SanRafaelSwell', '#stewardship', '#conservation', '#SanRafaelSwell', '#SanRafaelSwellRecreationArea', '#theswell', '#northforkcoalwash', '#bureauoflandmanagement', '#blm', '#tamariskremoval', '#tamarisk', '#saltcedar', '#invasive', '#utah', '#leavenotrace', '#lnt', '#clipping', '#cutting', '#slipperarch', '#thedrips', '#swaseysarch', '#volunteer', '#hiking', '#SidsMountainWildernessStudyArea', '#sidsmountain', '#swamping', '#sandstonecanyon', '#naturalarches'] | Time Stamp: 1641249176

Post_ID: 2742463949951579228 | Post_Code: CYPMG6qLbRc | Likes: 50 | Caption: DO YOU FEEL AT HOME WITH YOURSELF?<\br>These are some pictures of my new Brazilian home, which is beautiful and for which I am extremely grateful. But as nice as it may be, I know it is temporary. Now, all my homes up till now have been temporary of course, but I wasn't always accepting that: I would try to make myself stay at a place, just for the sake of some perceived duty, which didn't come from the heart and made me feel wrong. "You gotta settle down, Irene", a little voice inside my head would say, "You are an adult now, get serious already". Or, as a former boyfriend pointed out to me: "You can't live like an exchange student forever". Can't I? The truth is I don't know if I have ever felt truly at home anywhere I have lived: Spain, Italy, France, Belgium. I adapt easily, for sure. But home? That is a big word. In February 2020 I finally graduated from my doctorate and gave myself permission to travel the world, looking for a place worth of that title. Perfect timing, right? Fast-forward a pandemic and a burnout later, I can finally set off, taking my first trips within Europe to stay safe. I've had two professional burnouts in my 31 years of life, the first one was cured mostly with travel, together with psychotherapy. But surprise surprise, this second time I had gone beyond what my nervous system could sustain and no matter how many different therapies I was doing it never seemed to be enough. I spent 2021 trying all therapy forms I could find: yoga therapy, ayurveda, counselling, family constellations, energy healing, osteopathy, hypnosis, LNT... The solution? Learning how to truly put it all together in a holistic body-mind-spirit approach, to nourish and calm my nervous system, but also facing my deepest trauma and psychological patterns that had got me sick in first place. It's been hard work, but thanks to that I can now say that I feel at home with myself, wherever I go. And I know that soon, as I keep travelling, I will find a place where I will truly feel like staying. In the meantime, however, I am ok with not knowing, and just enjoying the ride. We get dropped off at a KFC/Taco Bell and eat two meals each. We then hip on a bus and head into town. We walk around a bit then meet up with @heyspamcake and @lianavit. PDF attempts to yogi us into the rodeo, but the folks at the ticket counter just let us go in anyways (the rodeo is halfway over when we get there). A bunch of people at the rodea are interested in what we're doing. We probably had five separate groups talk to us. We hike into a burn area. We had been in some before already, but this one is on a whole other level. There is absolutely nothing green here, it's very ashy, very little coverage from the sun. It's sad. We meet a couple who are actually familiar with Muncie, Indiana! After hiking some more we eventually get to a non-burnt area that is also our last big climb of Colorado. We get to the top, have a photo sesh, and then climb down. I grab enough water to get through the evening and next morning, as we'll be camping in between water sources. More people than ever are getting outside and enjoying our shared Public Lands which is great to see. <\br><\br>That said, there is sadly more litter, vandalism and sharply increased search and rescue calls due to a lack of preparedness for an outdoor experience. <\br><\br>In some cases, the quest to create content for social media channels trumps the need to put Nature First when creating said content. <\br><\br>As the outdoors become increasingly popular, lets work to make outdoor awareness just as popular. <\br><\br>As always, Adventure Responsibly!<\br><\br>If you like what we stand for and do, please share! <\br><\br>#adventureresponsibly #naturefirst  #wildernessculture #adventure #lnt #leaveitbetter #publiclands #nationalparks #hiking #camping #greatoutdoors #optoutside #protectthewild #cleanupyourshit #tagresponsibly #sidewiththeoutside #yourpubliclands #outdoorawareness | Tags: ['#adventureresponsibly', '#naturefirst', '#wildernessculture', '#adventure', '#lnt', '#leaveitbetter', '#publiclands', '#nationalparks', '#hiking', '#camping', '#greatoutdoors', '#optoutside', '#protectthewild', '#cleanupyourshit', '#tagresponsibly', '#sidewiththeoutside', '#yourpubliclands', '#outdoorawareness'] | Time Stamp: 1640710947

Vaughters, who farm still stands as one of the last remaining dairy landscapes in once-rural DeKalb County. Post_ID: 2735921597790966217 | Post_Code: CX38jKZplHJ | Likes: 413 | Caption: Everybody wants to reach the peak, but there is no growth on the top of a mountain. It is in the valley that we slog through, the lush grass and rich soil, learning and becoming what enables us to summit lifeâ€™s next peak.<\br>-Andy Andrews<\br><\br>I think that climbing mountains is like a therapy to me in a way that I can directly relate the climb to my journey through life.&nbsp; Whether it be romantic relationships, family/friends or your career.&nbsp; It all directly correlates with one another. <\br><\br>At the beginning as you're making your way along your approach, you're full of excitement, anticipation and fear of what's to come.. slogging through the valleys, through the bush, the ups and downs it takes, until you get a solid feel for the adventure ahead.&nbsp; You don't give up because it gets tough for a minute.. you fight through it, you show you're dedicated and committed to to the process, to reaching that summit.&nbsp; Just as you're getting to know you're journey, falling in love with that beaten path ahead of you - it finally comes into view, you see the big picture, you see what you really signed up for... and then it hits you like a bag of bricks. You realize damn this is a big objective with alot of risk!&nbsp; At this point in time you're left with 2 choices.. your fight or flight response kicks in, adrenaline starts pumping, body starts releasing serotonin and you wonder wtf you're doing here, is this really what you want to do!?&nbsp; For me.. if I've had the mental clarity to get myself into this position, then that answer is always yes!&nbsp; Staring that mountain in the face, absolutely terrified, absolutely humbled and ready to give it everything I have!! Theres no better feeling!&nbsp; From that point forward you're free! You send it with everything that you have! He was best known for his unique Jomon Zogan style of pottery, and was a master of many slip decorating and firing techniques for pottery. Throughout his career Shimaoka San worked collaboratively with a group of workers, students, and apprentices from Japan and abroad.<\br><\br>Width 8cm and 9cm<\br>Height 8cm and 9cm<\br><\br>Condition<\br>Unused work made in 1960-1970s.<\br>No chips. I know I've been a little absent lately, life has just been crazy busy these last few months!  But I figured I'd reintroduce myself for the new folks around here.<\br><\br>  My name is Brandon. I've been adventuring for the last 10 years, during that time it was mostly abandoned buildings, mines, caves and just alot of urban exploring.  It wasn't until I went through some of my lowest points in life that I really fell in love with nature, more specifically the mountains.  It took me falling to rock bottom in order for me to stand on my first summit.  That summit was mt Finlayson, it absolutely kicked my ass.. it took me 2 hours just to summit, but every grueling step, every ounce of sweat all became worth it standing at the top.  Standing there realizing how small I am, how small my problems are, just how free and at peace I felt for the first time in a long time.  It lit that fire inside of me like no other.  I was hooked!  Thats when the real fun began! Thats when I started to take myself more seriously, my body and mind more seriously.  Not only did it start an obsession with chasing that next peak, it started this amazing journey of self growth and spirituality.  I will be forever chasing that feeling.. that feeling of true inner peace that I felt that day ontop of little old mt Finlayson. <\br><\br>Never in my wildest imagination did I think there would be such an interest in my work here. Post_ID: 2732925147803899840 | Post_Code: CXtTPE4lVfA | Likes: 66 | Caption: Petrolia is a little town within Northern California's Lost Coast. This is an area so rugged and remote that the state could not build Highway 1 around it. in 1865, Petrolia was the location of California's first drilled oil well. It soon became too expensive to ship out of this area and the oil company failed. Today, few people live in Petrolia and the main industry is growing Marijuana. The Lost Coast is a breathtaking area to visit but beware. Both dispersed camping and open ground fires are strictly prohibited on park lands. <\br><\br>If you would like to sleep under stars in Hot Springs National Park, we encourage you to take advantage of the amenities that the Gulpha Gorge Campground has to offer. Most sites have full hook-ups, water, a picnic bench, and a fire ring. There are 40 sites that run on a first-come-first-serve basis for $30/night, and you can stay for up to 14 days. When I get closer it's some sort of facility for huskies. I feel better knowing it's not wild animals. I meet a group of Colorado Trail hikers and we chat for a bit, and I realize I forgot one of my meals at Sasha's. Later in the day I get up to higher elevation and am completely surrounded by fog. I have to climb over a knifes edge ride (a ridge that has steep slopes on both sides) without being able to see more than maybe twenty feet in any direction. I also climb up a difficult hill I didn't need to by accident. At this point there's no discernable trail and I keep climbing up and down in vaguely the right direction, but the sunset looks amazing so there's that bit of levity. After the sun sets I find a road, which is great because it's easy to follow and my phone is low on batteries. Post_ID: 2730003033394536169 | Post_Code: CXi60txOF7p | Likes: 149 | Caption: Diamorpha, the iconic red succulent that thrives in the thin soil of Arabia and Panola Mountains, is making its winter appearance! In order to survive the hot summers, this plant has adapted to a reverse growing season - it grows in the winter, blooms in spring, and then goes dormant by June. As you hike the rock outcrops, keep an eye for this beautiful little plant as you walk, and make sure to leave no trace by staying on the bare granite instead of the puddles, pits, and sandy patches. This year's winter growth is just beginning, so come back in January and February to see the diamorpha slowly take over the solution pits that dot the rock face.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>#ArabiaMountainNationalHeritageArea #ArabiaMountain #PanolaMountain #NationalHeritageArea#NationalPark #NationalHistoricSite #StatePark #GAStateParks #GeorgiaStatePark #Parks #Hiking #HikeLife #WanderNorthGA #AtlantaTrails #RespectThePark #LeaveNoTrace #OptOutside #RecreateResponsibly #LNT | Tags: ['#ArabiaMountainNationalHeritageArea', '#ArabiaMountain', '#PanolaMountain', '#NationalHeritageArea', '#NationalPark', '#NationalHistoricSite', '#StatePark', '#GAStateParks', '#GeorgiaStatePark', '#Parks', '#Hiking', '#HikeLife', '#WanderNorthGA', '#AtlantaTrails', '#RespectThePark', '#LeaveNoTrace', '#OptOutside', '#RecreateResponsibly', '#LNT'] | Time Stamp: 1639661743

Research your destination, weather, and road conditions prior to your trip. <\br><\br>â„ï¸ Plan and Prepare - Know your limits and your gear. Pack extra layers, waterproof clothing, and safety equipment or beacons for the backcountry. Have a Plan B in case you canâ€™t access your destination. <\br><\br>â„ï¸ Build an Inclusive Outdoors - Everyone deserves to experience a winter wonderland. Be an active part of making the outdoors safe, accessible, and welcoming for all identities and abilities. <\br><\br>â„ï¸ Respect Others - From mountain tops to shores to prairies, parking can be in short supply in the winter. Post_ID: 2729533878035915690 | Post_Code: CXhQJmyuaOq | Likes: 58 | Caption: Sign up for a guided mountain hike with Friends of Panola Mountain State Park to visit the conservation area - aka to hike on Panola Mountain itself. Carefully protected from most foot traffic to preserve the pristine rock outcrop ecosystem, Panola Mountain is an ecological treasure that can only be visited with a guide. Sign up by calling the Nature Center at (770) 389-7801.<\br>.<\br>Throughout the American Southeast, not many large, pristine rock outcrops remain. Two of the other local rock outcrops, or "monadnocks," Arabia Mountain and Stone Mountain, have both been heavily quarried and impacted by humans, for example. A similar fate has fallen many of the other monadnocks in the Southeast. At Panola Mountain, however, the story is different. Because the rock itself is no good for quarrying (the granite formation has a more brittle stone that cracks and splinters when broken). Luckily for us, that means that Panola Mountain has remained relatively untouched, with a pristine ecosystem that looks much as it has for thousands of years.<\br>Above: a guided hike on Panola Mountain.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>.<\br>#ArabiaMountainNationalHeritageArea #ArabiaMountain #PanolaMountain #NationalHeritageArea#NationalPark #NationalHistoricSite #StatePark #GAStateParks #GeorgiaStatePark #Parks #Hiking #HikeLife #WanderNorthGA #AtlantaTrails #RespectThePark #LeaveNoTrace #OptOutside #RecreateResponsibly #LNT | Tags: ['#ArabiaMountainNationalHeritageArea', '#ArabiaMountain', '#PanolaMountain', '#NationalHeritageArea', '#NationalPark', '#NationalHistoricSite', '#StatePark', '#GAStateParks', '#GeorgiaStatePark', '#Parks', '#Hiking', '#HikeLife', '#WanderNorthGA', '#AtlantaTrails', '#RespectThePark', '#LeaveNoTrace', '#OptOutside', '#RecreateResponsibly', '#LNT'] | Time Stamp: 1639605816

Post_ID: 2728655551543416569 | Post_Code: CXeIcRgJJb5 | Likes: 59 | Caption: ***Dolly Sods designated as LNT â€œHot Spot.â€***<\br>â€¢<\br>â€¢<\br>The Leave No Trace (LNT) organization has announced that the Dolly Sods Wilderness has been designated as one of its 2022 Hot Spots, and will devote special attention and resources to the impacts which threaten its natural character. There has been a steady rise in visitation at Dolly Sods over the past decade, with a significant spike during the pandemic. This had led to significant impact on and degradation of the wilderness character of Dolly Sods. The LNT organization will coordinate with the Monongahela National Forest and WVHCâ€™s Dolly Sods Wilderness Stewards to plan training, workshops and community events to address specific issues related to the effects of high visitor use. These include the proliferation and impact of campsites, vegetation loss, and appropriate backcountry practices. We will share more information and announcements of events as plans develop. Please check our website to learn more about our Wilderness Stewards program and find out how you can help. Post_ID: 2728580766430997761 | Post_Code: CXd3cAcFS0B | Likes: 42 | Caption: A mysterious field full of what appears to be satellite dishes are searching the skies in the Eastern Sierra. The Owens Valley Radio Observatory is just outside of Bishop, California in the little town of Big Pine, and the satellite dishes are actually radio telescopes and antennas. The Owens Valley Radio Observatory is one of the largest university-operated radio observatories in the world. There are a number of different research projects going on at OVRO, home to more than a dozen radio telescopes and even more antennas. A lot of what goes on here is highly technical and not that visual. These telescope dishes record radio waves that are processed in complex computers, then converted into data that only scientists can read. The telescopes were built in the Owens Valley because it has clear skies and is far away from radio electrical interference. Essentially, it's in the middle of nowhere. The telescopes come in all shapes and sizes and search all sorts of things. The largest dish is 40-meters, and it studies black holes. A series of medium dishes locate Fast Radio Bursts and small ground level antenna looking devices study something referred to as red shifts.â <\br>#Caltech @owensvalley @easternsierra @bigearsâ <\br>â <\br>#travelgram #instatravel #adventure #explore #photooftheday #nature #vacation #traveling #instadaily #bartellsbackroads #abc10tv #pitstop #roadsideattraction #california #norcal #socal #morningblend #LNT #DronesOfCalifornia #roadtrip #californiahistoricallandmark #californiadreaming #californialoveâ  | Tags: ['#Caltech', '#travelgram', '#instatravel', '#adventure', '#explore', '#photooftheday', '#nature', '#vacation', '#traveling', '#instadaily', '#bartellsbackroads', '#abc10tv', '#pitstop', '#roadsideattraction', '#california', '#norcal', '#socal', '#morningblend', '#LNT', '#DronesOfCalifornia', '#roadtrip', '#californiahistoricallandmark', '#californiadreaming', '#californialove\u2060'] | Time Stamp: 1639492196
